Accuracy

To measure performance, we need to make predictions and then test the accuracy of predictions. We can do this using a few methods:

Let’s test a sample prediction with the first 5 results, predicting they all have surivived

library(caret)
## Loading required package: lattice
## Loading required package: ggplot2
accuracy_score <- function(pred, truth) {
  # Function to test accuracy for survivor outcomes from Titanic dataset
  # pred & truth converted to factors for xtab/confusionMatrix
  pred <- factor(pred, levels = c(0,1))
  truth <- factor(truth, levels = c(0,1))
  xtab <- table(pred, truth)
  cm <- confusionMatrix(xtab, positive = "1")
  print(paste("Predictions have an accuracy of", scales::percent(cm$overall[1])))
}

accuracy_score(rep(1,5), outcomes[1:5])
## [1] "Predictions have an accuracy of 60%"

Our accuracy here would be:

Making Predictions

Since most people did not survive the Titanic, our null hyopthesis for any model will be based on a model that assumes no one survived. Any model that does not beat this naive model is a bad model.

predictions_0 <- function(data) {
  predictions = rep(0, nrow(data))
}
predictions <- predictions_0(data)
accuracy_score(predictions, outcomes)
## [1] "Predictions have an accuracy of 61.6%"

Effect of Sex

Rather than create a function to plot based on a feature, we will use the rather intuitive ggplot2 syntax to quickly build plots.

survival_labs <- c("Did Not Survive", "Survived")
ggplot(data = data, aes(Sex, fill=outcomes)) + 
  geom_bar(position="dodge") + 
  scale_fill_discrete(labels = survival_labs)

Since we know more females as a percentage survived than males, our next model will perform a simple prediction based on sex.

predictions_1 <- function(data) {
  as.numeric(data$Sex == "female")
}
accuracy_score(predictions_1(data), outcomes)
## [1] "Predictions have an accuracy of 78.7%"

Effects of Age

Let’s look at the effects of age on survival

ggplot(data=data, aes(Age, fill = outcomes)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth=10, boundary = 0, alpha = 0.5, position = "identity") +
  facet_wrap(~ Sex) +
  scale_fill_discrete(labels = survival_labs)
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

We see that males < 10 have a better survival rate than males > 10 so let’s add that to our model

predictions_2 <- function(data) {
  c1 <- data$Sex == 'female'
  c2 <- data$Age < 10
  z <- pmax(c1, c2)
  return(z)
}
accuracy_score(predictions_2(data), outcomes)
## [1] "Predictions have an accuracy of 78.9%"

Now that we have a decent model, let’s try and build a better model using some data science methods available to us.

We’ll first split the dataset into training, test, and calibration sets. This is not strictly necessary as we are not seeking to predict surivival rates of future Titanic sinkings, but it’s a good practice and so we perform it here for demonstration purposes.

set.seed(1912)
full_data$test_set <- sample(c(1,2,3), size = nrow(full_data), replace = TRUE, 
                            prob = c(0.8, 0.1, 0.1))
d_train <- filter(full_data, test_set == 1)
d_cal <- filter(full_data, test_set == 2)
d_test <- filter(full_data, test_set == 3)

Here we see strong associations between SibSp and Parch (Number of Siblings/Spouses and Number of Parents/Children) which makes sense given that people with spouses are often related to children with parents. There is also a strong relationship between Pclass and Fare, which also makes sense as higher-class cabins are usually more expensive.

There’s a surprising moderate negative relationship between class and age, as it appears older passengers are also lower-class as well.

In our first attempt, we will try using generalized linear models to perform logistic regression using these variables. Let’s plot surivival against the variables we think might be worth investigating.

# Build a simple model
mdl_sex <- glm(Survived ~ Sex, data = d_train, family=binomial(link='logit'))

Our simple logit model gives us an accuracy of 78.9%, not bad but we can do better.

What if we tried a linear discremant analysis (LDA)?

Accuracy is now much closer between the training and calibration datasets, but not near the 80% that we striving for. Let’s try another model, this time using decision trees. Decision trees have the added bonus of being highly interpretable, at the expense of lower performance than more complex models. A price I am willing to pay in this example.

# Little more complex
mdl_all <- rpart(Survived ~ Sex + Age + Pclass + Parch, data = d_train, method = 'class')
rpart.plot(mdl_all, type = 4)

We can see that a decision tree offers intuitive ways to understand the logic behind the algorithm. Let’s test the decision tree on our calibration data to see how well it performs.

mdl_pred <- predict(mdl_all, type = "class")
table(mdl_pred, d_train$Survived)
##         
## mdl_pred   0   1
##        0 409  96
##        1  46 185
accuracy_score(mdl_pred, d_train$Survived)
## [1] "Predictions have an accuracy of 80.7%"
mdl_pred <- predict(mdl_all, newdata = d_cal, type = "class")
table(mdl_pred, d_cal$Survived)
##         
## mdl_pred  0  1
##        0 38 13
##        1  5 22
accuracy_score(mdl_pred, d_cal$Survived)
## [1] "Predictions have an accuracy of 76.9%"

Accuracy drops to 76.9% on the calibration dataset. Let’s try using every variable to see if that improves calibration results.

mdl_all2 <- rpart(Survived ~ Pclass + Sex + Age + SibSp + Parch + Fare + Embarked, 
                  data = d_train, method = 'class')
rpart.plot(mdl_all2, uniform = TRUE)

mdl_pred <- predict(mdl_all2, type = "class")
accuracy_score(mdl_pred, d_train$Survived)
## [1] "Predictions have an accuracy of 84.5%"
mdl_pred <- predict(mdl_all2, newdata = d_cal, type = "class")
table(mdl_pred, d_cal$Survived)
##         
## mdl_pred  0  1
##        0 39 12
##        1  4 23
accuracy_score(mdl_pred, d_cal$Survived)
## [1] "Predictions have an accuracy of 79.5%"

Including all terms improves accuracy to 79.5% in calibration. We can play with some of the rpart settings to see how we can tune accuracy

control = rpart.control(cp = 0.001, maxdepth = 4, minsplit = 1, minbucket = 2, surrogatestyle = 1)
mdl_all3 <- rpart(Survived ~ Pclass + Sex + Age + SibSp + Parch + Fare + Embarked, 
                  data = d_train, method = 'class', control = control)
rpart.plot(mdl_all3, type = 4)

mdl_pred <- predict(mdl_all3, type = "class")
accuracy_score(mdl_pred, d_train$Survived)
## [1] "Predictions have an accuracy of 83.3%"
mdl_pred <- predict(mdl_all3, newdata = d_cal, type = "class")
table(mdl_pred, d_cal$Survived)
##         
## mdl_pred  0  1
##        0 39 12
##        1  4 23
accuracy_score(mdl_pred, d_cal$Survived)
## [1] "Predictions have an accuracy of 79.5%"

With some tuning, we improve prediction to 79.5% in the calibration set. This is a pretty good result, so let’s check against our test data.

mdl_pred <- predict(mdl_all3, newdata = d_test, type = "class")
accuracy_score(mdl_pred, d_test$Survived)
## [1] "Predictions have an accuracy of 84.4%"

Great! Test prediction is even higher than calibration prediction. Let’s use the entire dataset to build our final model.

library(rpart.plot)
mdl_tree_final <- rpart(Survived ~ Pclass + Sex + Age + SibSp + Parch + Fare + Embarked, 
                  data = full_data, method = 'class', control = control)
accuracy_score(predict(mdl_tree_final, type = 'class'), full_data$Survived)
## [1] "Predictions have an accuracy of 82.8%"
rpart.plot(mdl_tree_final, type = 4)
